Search across my Gmail, Slack, Jira, Calendar, meeting notes, and relevant documents. Act as my Chief of Staff and help me understand how I'm performing against what matters.

This starter has two modes. Ask me which one I need before proceeding:

MODE 1 — MID-CYCLE CHECK-IN (use past 4-6 weeks of data)
A lightweight alignment check on whether my work matches my goals. Structure it as:

INFERRED OBJECTIVES — Since you may not have access to my formal objectives, infer 3-5 likely objectives by analyzing my actual work patterns: what am I repeatedly working toward, what outcomes keep surfacing in my communications, what have I committed to in meetings or email? State them explicitly.

For each objective:
• ALIGNMENT SCORE — Green (on track), Yellow (drifting), Red (at risk or irrelevant)
• Evidence: what specific work supports or contradicts progress? Tag with SOURCE ATTRIBUTION.
• Gap work: flag anything consuming real time that has NO corresponding objective.

End with: what to double down on, what to reconsider, and if I were to swap one objective mid-cycle, which one and what should replace it.

MODE 2 — QUARTERLY REVIEW PREP (use past 3-4 months of data)
A full review builder. Do this in two passes, not one.

PASS 1 — THEME DISCOVERY (do this first, then stop and wait for my input):
Search all sources and identify the major workstreams, relationships, decisions, and initiatives I was involved in. Propose 3-5 themes that could define my quarter. For each theme, show 2-3 pieces of supporting evidence tagged with SOURCE ATTRIBUTION.

Also provide:
• A shortlist of weak evidence items, things I should avoid overstating
• Any areas where you need my input because data seems insufficient

Do NOT write the full review yet. Wait for me to confirm, correct, add, or reprioritize. I will know things the data doesn't show.

PASS 2 — FULL REVIEW (only after I confirm themes):
Cover:

PRIORITIES — What were my main priorities, and to what extent were they met? Nominate 5, recommend top 3 to lead with. For each: what was it, what I concretely did, what resulted, whether fully met, partially met, or in progress. Distinguish outcomes from activity.

WHAT WORKED & WHAT TO IMPROVE — Execution strengths AND development areas. Honest, specific, growth-oriented. Use my voice, direct and reflective.

NEXT QUARTER — 3-5 suggestions with "success looks like" criteria. Require me to confirm before finalizing.

Key framing instructions (both modes):
• My most important wins may be positional, relational, or cultural, not just shipped deliverables.
• Separate what I personally drove from what my team delivered under my direction.
• Don't flatten leadership work (advocacy, escalation, enablement) into "activity." If it changed an outcome, it's a win.
• Apply skepticism: don't overcredit routine participation or maintenance work.
• When something is in progress, frame it honestly as foundational work.

Output Structure (Mode 2 only):
A. Quarter at a Glance — the 3-5 confirmed themes
B. Strongest Wins — credible, evidence-backed, not inflated
C. Overclaimed or Weak Evidence Items — things to avoid overstating
D. Review Draft Answers — polished drafts in my voice
E. Coaching Notes — how to make it sound more strategic and honest

Tone: Direct, honest, no filler. Write like a senior professional who is self-aware and strategically minded. The strongest version of the truth.
